And I would think in
the day, maybe exposure

00:15:30.700 --> 00:15:34.580 align:middle line:84%
to metals and toxins we didn't
really understand at the time,

00:15:34.580 --> 00:15:35.380 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:15:35.380 --> 00:15:36.760 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: One of
the rabbit holes

00:15:36.760 --> 00:15:39.310 align:middle line:84%
I had to explore when
writing this book

00:15:39.310 --> 00:15:43.670 align:middle line:84%
was the difference in
madness in that era from now.

00:15:43.670 --> 00:15:47.740 align:middle line:84%
And so rather than try to
engage with that question

00:15:47.740 --> 00:15:49.300 align:middle line:84%
in every other
sentence of the book,

00:15:49.300 --> 00:15:52.420 align:middle line:84%
I created a compendium
of madness perspectives

00:15:52.420 --> 00:15:56.450 align:middle line:84%
in my appendix so I
can refer to that.

00:15:56.450 --> 00:16:00.220 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, things were
very, very different.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:02.680 align:middle line:84%
When people arrived at the
asylum, much of the time,

00:16:02.680 --> 00:16:04.250 align:middle line:84%
they were malnourished
and exhausted.

00:16:04.250 --> 00:16:06.625 align:middle line:84%
So the first thing that was
done was to give them a rest,

00:16:06.625 --> 00:16:09.783 align:middle line:84%
put them in bed, give them
really good nutrition,

00:16:09.783 --> 00:16:11.200 align:middle line:84%
which state of the
art at the time

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:13.052 align:middle line:84%
involved warm milk
was one of the--

00:16:13.052 --> 00:16:15.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Warm milk was
really prominent, yeah.

00:16:15.010 --> 00:16:17.350 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: And the milk was a
high quality and after that--

00:16:17.350 --> 00:16:18.370 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Directly
from the cows,

00:16:18.370 --> 00:16:19.480 align:middle line:90%
not pasteurized and all that.

00:16:19.480 --> 00:16:20.438 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: That's right.

00:16:20.438 --> 00:16:21.250 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:16:21.250 --> 00:16:23.860 align:middle line:84%
Also these asylums work
best when they weren't like

00:16:23.860 --> 00:16:26.500 align:middle line:84%
2,000-person,
2,000-bed facilities,

00:16:26.500 --> 00:16:29.782 align:middle line:84%
which is what they grew into
later on and which turned out

00:16:29.782 --> 00:16:31.990 align:middle line:84%
to be their demise because
how can you do really good

00:16:31.990 --> 00:16:34.360 align:middle line:90%
homeopathy with 2,000 clients?

00:16:34.360 --> 00:16:35.160 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:16:35.160 --> 00:16:40.150 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: But yeah, bit by
bit, they were really nurtured.

00:16:40.150 --> 00:16:42.550 align:middle line:84%
They were told, you're going
to be here indefinitely,

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:43.450 align:middle line:90%
we're going to get you together.

00:16:43.450 --> 00:16:46.075 align:middle line:84%
We're not going to rush you back
into your dysfunctional family

00:16:46.075 --> 00:16:47.465 align:middle line:90%
or into the community.

00:16:47.465 --> 00:16:49.090 align:middle line:84%
We're going to let
you engage in things

00:16:49.090 --> 00:16:51.610 align:middle line:84%
that are absolutely pleasurable
and beneficial to you,

00:16:51.610 --> 00:16:55.480 align:middle line:84%
let you work on a craft, let
you participate in the garden,

00:16:55.480 --> 00:16:58.930 align:middle line:84%
let you listen to and
create music, write letters.

00:16:58.930 --> 00:17:01.855 align:middle line:84%
Clara Barrus, who's one
of the heroes of my book--

00:17:01.855 --> 00:17:04.210 align:middle line:84%
there is the other Clara
Bar-- was Clara Barton, who

00:17:04.210 --> 00:17:07.510 align:middle line:84%
was the very, very famous
angel of the battlefield

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:11.020 align:middle line:84%
in my opinion, had this
counterpart in Clara Barrus who

00:17:11.020 --> 00:17:15.115 align:middle line:84%
was wrote this fantastic book
called "Nursing the Insane."

00:17:15.115 --> 00:17:17.560 align:middle line:84%
A fantastic book,
really brilliant book,

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.400 align:middle line:90%
very compassionate person.

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:22.569 align:middle line:84%
And so she would have them
engage in giggle classes,

00:17:22.569 --> 00:17:23.810 align:middle line:90%
get people to laugh.

00:17:23.810 --> 00:17:24.610 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Giggle.

00:17:24.610 --> 00:17:25.485 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, giggle therapy.

00:17:25.485 --> 00:17:26.560 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Giggle classes.

00:17:26.560 --> 00:17:27.602 align:middle line:90%
It was one thing she did.

00:17:27.602 --> 00:17:30.850 align:middle line:84%
But she had just tremendous
respect for the mentally ill.

00:17:30.850 --> 00:17:33.520 align:middle line:84%
And she imparted
that to the nurses.

00:17:33.520 --> 00:17:37.000 align:middle line:84%
So as I say, they
engaged with the clients

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.290 align:middle line:84%
actively in terms of trying to
release them from the delusions

00:17:41.290 --> 00:17:43.915 align:middle line:84%
that they had with
patience and kindness.

00:17:43.915 --> 00:17:46.780 align:middle line:90%


00:17:46.780 --> 00:17:49.630 align:middle line:84%
It was very different from
the nursing obligations today.

00:17:49.630 --> 00:17:51.130 align:middle line:84%
Nurses are wonderful
today, but they

00:17:51.130 --> 00:17:52.713 align:middle line:84%
don't have the time
or the opportunity

00:17:52.713 --> 00:17:55.180 align:middle line:84%
and this just does
not happen anywhere,

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:57.640 align:middle line:84%
not in a psychiatrist
office, not

00:17:57.640 --> 00:18:00.220 align:middle line:84%
in any of these
mental health clinics.

00:18:00.220 --> 00:18:02.650 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because no one's
given that valuable commodity

00:18:02.650 --> 00:18:03.085 align:middle line:90%
of time.

00:18:03.085 --> 00:18:03.885 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yes.

00:18:03.885 --> 00:18:06.490 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And when you
write about her and some

00:18:06.490 --> 00:18:08.990 align:middle line:84%
of the other nurses, it's
like as you said earlier,

00:18:08.990 --> 00:18:11.200 align:middle line:90%
they're like paragons of virtue.

00:18:11.200 --> 00:18:15.220 align:middle line:84%
And she wrote a directive on
what a good nurse ought to be.

00:18:15.220 --> 00:18:18.193 align:middle line:84%
Maybe you can share a
little bit of that with us.

00:18:18.193 --> 00:18:20.110 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: Better if you
read her actual words.

00:18:20.110 --> 00:18:21.130 align:middle line:90%
She's quite a good writer.

00:18:21.130 --> 00:18:21.310 align:middle line:90%
But--

00:18:21.310 --> 00:18:22.310 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: She was, yeah.

00:18:22.310 --> 00:18:24.700 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: --basically being
free from discouragement,

00:18:24.700 --> 00:18:26.710 align:middle line:84%
paying very close
attention to the clients,

00:18:26.710 --> 00:18:29.920 align:middle line:84%
to their cleanliness, being
very observant to what they did

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:33.190 align:middle line:84%
and what they said, not
engaging them with arguments.

00:18:33.190 --> 00:18:35.740 align:middle line:84%
A lot of it's advanced
placement common sense.

00:18:35.740 --> 00:18:39.070 align:middle line:84%
How would you-- if you were
to deal with your client as

00:18:39.070 --> 00:18:41.770 align:middle line:90%
you would with a sick relative.

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:43.462 align:middle line:90%
Kind of the same thing.

00:18:43.462 --> 00:18:44.545 align:middle line:90%
It's hugely compassionate.

00:18:44.545 --> 00:18:46.270 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Very,
very compassionate.

00:18:46.270 --> 00:18:49.805 align:middle line:84%
So here you have
bucolic settings.

00:18:49.805 --> 00:18:50.605 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:18:50.605 --> 00:18:51.940 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: This was
really-- nature

00:18:51.940 --> 00:18:53.185 align:middle line:90%
was part of it having space.

00:18:53.185 --> 00:18:55.750 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: And there was
more nature around then.

00:18:55.750 --> 00:18:57.400 align:middle line:90%
They picked beautiful settings.

00:18:57.400 --> 00:18:59.620 align:middle line:90%
And they had a lot of land.

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:03.100 align:middle line:84%
And homeopathy was not
controversial back then.

00:19:03.100 --> 00:19:07.300 align:middle line:84%
And the states would give
them huge land grants.

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.030 align:middle line:84%
The states would
subsidize these places.

00:19:10.030 --> 00:19:12.138 align:middle line:84%
And when they're
operated correctly,

00:19:12.138 --> 00:19:13.430 align:middle line:90%
they were even self-sufficient.

00:19:13.430 --> 00:19:15.260 align:middle line:84%
I call them utopias like
the Middletown Asylum--

00:19:15.260 --> 00:19:16.390 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, very utopian.

00:19:16.390 --> 00:19:18.015 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: --was able
to sustain itself.

00:19:18.015 --> 00:19:21.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Let's talk about
that and Dr. Selden Talcott

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:23.380 align:middle line:84%
in his role in all
of that because he's

00:19:23.380 --> 00:19:24.530 align:middle line:90%
another hero in the book.

00:19:24.530 --> 00:19:25.330 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:19:25.330 --> 00:19:26.680 align:middle line:90%
He's a hero in my book.

00:19:26.680 --> 00:19:32.240 align:middle line:84%
So he was a Civil War physician,
had a very extensive training

00:19:32.240 --> 00:19:33.040 align:middle line:90%
in homeopathy.

00:19:33.040 --> 00:19:37.120 align:middle line:84%
He actually ran a homeopathic
alcoholism facility

00:19:37.120 --> 00:19:40.990 align:middle line:84%
in New York at Ward's Island,
just an absolutely wonderful,

00:19:40.990 --> 00:19:44.530 align:middle line:84%
hugely respected person,
disciple of a homeopath

00:19:44.530 --> 00:19:46.480 align:middle line:84%
by the name of
Samuel Lilienthal.

00:19:46.480 --> 00:19:48.090 align:middle line:84%
And he was the
second superintend

00:19:48.090 --> 00:19:50.850 align:middle line:84%
in Middletown Homeopathic
Hospital for the Insane

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:52.870 align:middle line:90%
as it was called then.

00:19:52.870 --> 00:19:57.870 align:middle line:84%
And he was involved in
its every aspect of it--

00:19:57.870 --> 00:20:00.870 align:middle line:84%
well, the design was there,
but he refined that a lot.

00:20:00.870 --> 00:20:02.280 align:middle line:90%
But he ran a tight ship.

00:20:02.280 --> 00:20:05.760 align:middle line:90%
It was budgetary on target.

00:20:05.760 --> 00:20:08.040 align:middle line:84%
The thing that he did that
really made him stand out

00:20:08.040 --> 00:20:10.395 align:middle line:90%
was using baseball as a therapy.

00:20:10.395 --> 00:20:11.720 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:13.470 align:middle line:84%
That's kind of where
your interest in this

00:20:13.470 --> 00:20:14.170 align:middle line:90%
started, right?

00:20:14.170 --> 00:20:15.420 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: It was an
easy thing to do.

00:20:15.420 --> 00:20:16.795 align:middle line:84%
There was a baseball
field there.

00:20:16.795 --> 00:20:18.660 align:middle line:84%
And initially, some
of the staff members

00:20:18.660 --> 00:20:21.120 align:middle line:84%
and the doctors and the
patients played together.

00:20:21.120 --> 00:20:24.150 align:middle line:84%
And he noticed that
the patients there were

00:20:24.150 --> 00:20:25.710 align:middle line:90%
watching this very intently.

00:20:25.710 --> 00:20:27.330 align:middle line:90%
And he was an observant man.

00:20:27.330 --> 00:20:29.250 align:middle line:84%
He said, baseball seems
to make a difference.

00:20:29.250 --> 00:20:31.500 align:middle line:84%
They were all better when
they were watching baseball.

00:20:31.500 --> 00:20:33.510 align:middle line:84%
So he created this
fantastic team.

00:20:33.510 --> 00:20:37.410 align:middle line:84%
He poached players from local
teams and created this team,

00:20:37.410 --> 00:20:39.930 align:middle line:84%
not with the inmates
playing for it,

00:20:39.930 --> 00:20:41.490 align:middle line:90%
but to represent the asylum.

00:20:41.490 --> 00:20:44.190 align:middle line:84%
And the team was
called the Asylums.

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:45.870 align:middle line:84%
And they were an
absolute powerhouse.

00:20:45.870 --> 00:20:48.300 align:middle line:84%
They had a future Hall
of Famer, Jack Chesbro.

00:20:48.300 --> 00:20:50.520 align:middle line:84%
And they played Major
League teams to a stand off,

00:20:50.520 --> 00:20:52.890 align:middle line:84%
and big crowds came
to watch the games.

00:20:52.890 --> 00:20:55.710 align:middle line:84%
And even the craziest
of the clients

00:20:55.710 --> 00:20:58.920 align:middle line:84%
would come out in rapt
attention watch this.

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:00.870 align:middle line:90%
But he was also--

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:02.683 align:middle line:84%
the Middletown
facility was what I

00:21:02.683 --> 00:21:04.350 align:middle line:84%
call the Mother Church
for this movement

00:21:04.350 --> 00:21:07.560 align:middle line:84%
because it was the really
most the biggest, the most

00:21:07.560 --> 00:21:09.360 align:middle line:90%
successful mental health asylum.

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:12.960 align:middle line:84%
So many other psychiatrists,
homeopathic psychiatrists

00:21:12.960 --> 00:21:14.640 align:middle line:90%
went and did internships there.

00:21:14.640 --> 00:21:16.830 align:middle line:84%
And then they went and
worked at other facilities

00:21:16.830 --> 00:21:21.720 align:middle line:84%
like at Butler Asylum in
Providence, Fergus Falls

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:24.600 align:middle line:90%
in Minnesota, Westborough.

00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:27.870 align:middle line:84%
And then when they completed
their careers there,

00:21:27.870 --> 00:21:30.930 align:middle line:84%
they would often open
small sanitariums,

00:21:30.930 --> 00:21:32.370 align:middle line:90%
private sanitariums.

00:21:32.370 --> 00:21:37.020 align:middle line:84%
But Talcott was just a
hugely respected homeopath.

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:39.600 align:middle line:84%
We have in our material
medico, the software

00:21:39.600 --> 00:21:42.930 align:middle line:84%
for a practitioner, one of
his books that we refer to.

00:21:42.930 --> 00:21:45.800 align:middle line:84%
So he was a successful
man on many levels.

00:21:45.800 --> 00:21:48.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So one thing
you talked about a little

00:21:48.360 --> 00:21:50.250 align:middle line:90%
bit ago was the alcoholism part.

00:21:50.250 --> 00:21:52.440 align:middle line:84%
So this I found
intriguing in the book.

00:21:52.440 --> 00:21:56.340 align:middle line:84%
Following the Civil War,
there was a huge issue

00:21:56.340 --> 00:22:00.480 align:middle line:84%
with alcoholism, just the
disorientation of coming back

00:22:00.480 --> 00:22:03.650 align:middle line:84%
from such an incredibly
brutal situation.

00:22:03.650 --> 00:22:05.100 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:22:05.100 --> 00:22:09.000 align:middle line:84%
There's a book called
"The Empire of Suffering"

00:22:09.000 --> 00:22:12.880 align:middle line:84%
that goes into the carnage,
what the problems the Civil War

00:22:12.880 --> 00:22:13.680 align:middle line:90%
caused.

00:22:13.680 --> 00:22:15.150 align:middle line:84%
That was interesting for
me to learn about that.

00:22:15.150 --> 00:22:15.950 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:22:15.950 --> 00:22:18.240 align:middle line:10%
>>KANTOR: Back in those
days, I didn't know this,

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:20.130 align:middle line:10%
people were deeply
invested in the idea

00:22:20.130 --> 00:22:23.940 align:middle line:10%
that of the resurrection
of the body physically.

00:22:23.940 --> 00:22:27.570 align:middle line:84%
Actually, when you died,
somehow through this belief

00:22:27.570 --> 00:22:29.640 align:middle line:84%
in Christianity, the body
would be resurrected.

00:22:29.640 --> 00:22:32.520 align:middle line:84%
And there was also
a high premium

00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:35.640 align:middle line:84%
put on the value of one's
last words as you were dying.

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:38.310 align:middle line:84%
Dying was not such a
big deal as the fact

00:22:38.310 --> 00:22:40.490 align:middle line:84%
that you would give your
last words to describe

00:22:40.490 --> 00:22:42.990 align:middle line:84%
how your life was meaningful
and that you didn't mind dying.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.420 align:middle line:90%
The Civil War blew that apart.

00:22:45.420 --> 00:22:46.710 align:middle line:90%
The bodies could not be found.

00:22:46.710 --> 00:22:49.350 align:middle line:84%
When they were found,
they were obliterated.

00:22:49.350 --> 00:22:53.970 align:middle line:84%
There were very few inspiring
last words that were uttered.

00:22:53.970 --> 00:22:57.210 align:middle line:84%
The people went into a
gigantic crisis of grief.

00:22:57.210 --> 00:23:00.930 align:middle line:84%
And this is a primary reason
why all these mental hospitals

00:23:00.930 --> 00:23:04.170 align:middle line:84%
sprung up, and also,
I imagine alcoholism.

00:23:04.170 --> 00:23:06.680 align:middle line:84%
But the country was always
heavily into alcohol,

00:23:06.680 --> 00:23:07.770 align:middle line:90%
it was used--

00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:10.395 align:middle line:90%
people would drink--

00:23:10.395 --> 00:23:11.460 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:23:11.460 --> 00:23:14.310 align:middle line:84%
I was reading about that, the
amount of alcohol per capita

00:23:14.310 --> 00:23:16.290 align:middle line:90%
that was drunk back then.

00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:17.160 align:middle line:90%
Holy cow!

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:19.485 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: There's a great
book called "Saloon Culture."

00:23:19.485 --> 00:23:21.750 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They were
anesthetizing heavily

00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:23.980 align:middle line:84%
across the country,
men and women.

00:23:23.980 --> 00:23:24.780 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:25.050 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:25.050 --> 00:23:25.800 align:middle line:90%
People drank heavily.

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:26.980 align:middle line:90%
And that was a big problem.

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:30.030 align:middle line:84%
And so what we now
call tardive dyskinesia

00:23:30.030 --> 00:23:31.350 align:middle line:90%
in those days was called--

00:23:31.350 --> 00:23:32.850 align:middle line:90%
had a different derivation.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:35.527 align:middle line:84%
Then it was delirium tremens,
late stages of alcoholism.

00:23:35.527 --> 00:23:37.110 align:middle line:84%
You'd just be sitting
there trembling.

00:23:37.110 --> 00:23:37.500 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:23:37.500 --> 00:23:37.890 align:middle line:90%
The shakes.

00:23:37.890 --> 00:23:38.550 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:23:38.550 --> 00:23:40.550 align:middle line:84%
And homeopathy can
ameliorate that too somewhat.

00:23:40.550 --> 00:23:43.170 align:middle line:84%
There are books on homeopathic
treatment of inebriation.

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:47.130 align:middle line:84%
But getting to an absolute
cure when you're that far gone

00:23:47.130 --> 00:23:48.660 align:middle line:90%
is a bridge too far.

00:23:48.660 --> 00:23:51.100 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What about
drug addiction?

00:23:51.100 --> 00:23:52.350 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: What, today or then?

00:23:52.350 --> 00:23:53.820 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: No, today.

00:23:53.820 --> 00:23:56.520 align:middle line:84%
Homeopathic approaches to
breaking drug addictions.

00:23:56.520 --> 00:23:57.320 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:23:57.320 --> 00:23:58.278 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely, we do that.

00:23:58.278 --> 00:24:00.780 align:middle line:90%
We have to detox someone.

00:24:00.780 --> 00:24:03.900 align:middle line:84%
Well, that would be a
combination of actually using--

00:24:03.900 --> 00:24:06.810 align:middle line:84%
making homeopathic
preparation from the drug

00:24:06.810 --> 00:24:10.000 align:middle line:84%
that has addicted you so that
you can gradually wean yourself

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:10.800 align:middle line:90%
from it.

00:24:10.800 --> 00:24:11.910 align:middle line:90%
At the same time, you would--

00:24:11.910 --> 00:24:13.535 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Kind of
like nicotine patches

00:24:13.535 --> 00:24:15.497 align:middle line:90%
almost, but not exactly.

00:24:15.497 --> 00:24:17.830 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: People confuse
homeopathy with lots of things.

00:24:17.830 --> 00:24:20.190 align:middle line:84%
So it's not
desensitization therapy,

00:24:20.190 --> 00:24:24.777 align:middle line:84%
although when you're using the
dilute versions of the drugs,

00:24:24.777 --> 00:24:25.860 align:middle line:90%
it is something like that.

00:24:25.860 --> 00:24:26.100 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:24:26.100 --> 00:24:27.120 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: But then
you would also

00:24:27.120 --> 00:24:29.580 align:middle line:84%
incorporate the constitutional
remedy and other support

00:24:29.580 --> 00:24:32.310 align:middle line:84%
remedies and maybe remedies
made from neurotransmitters

00:24:32.310 --> 00:24:34.450 align:middle line:84%
to help the person
get to the other side.

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:36.900 align:middle line:84%
But it's a matter of
creating a good game

00:24:36.900 --> 00:24:39.235 align:middle line:84%
plan as opposed to
saying, we're just

00:24:39.235 --> 00:24:40.860 align:middle line:84%
going to cure you
with this one remedy.

00:24:40.860 --> 00:24:43.110 align:middle line:84%
That's what I mean by people
being sicker than before.

00:24:43.110 --> 00:24:44.050 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:24:44.050 --> 00:24:44.850 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:24:44.850 --> 00:24:46.683 align:middle line:84%
You just said something
I didn't know about.

00:24:46.683 --> 00:24:48.400 align:middle line:84%
Remedies made from
neurotransmitters?

00:24:48.400 --> 00:24:49.200 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:24:49.200 --> 00:24:51.840 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Tell us a little bit
about that because right now,

00:24:51.840 --> 00:24:54.745 align:middle line:84%
we've got all kinds of issues
going on with our brain.

00:24:54.745 --> 00:24:55.545 align:middle line:90%
Our brains.

00:24:55.545 --> 00:24:58.410 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: Well, the avatar of
that is a homeopath in Holland

00:24:58.410 --> 00:25:00.660 align:middle line:90%
by the name of Ton Jansen.

00:25:00.660 --> 00:25:02.525 align:middle line:84%
And his brand of
homeopathy is probably

00:25:02.525 --> 00:25:03.900 align:middle line:84%
going to revolutionize
the field.

00:25:03.900 --> 00:25:05.940 align:middle line:84%
It's practiced
extensively in Europe.

00:25:05.940 --> 00:25:09.300 align:middle line:84%
And my colleague, Ruma
Biswas is a proponent of his.

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:12.577 align:middle line:90%
And that takes a lot of work.

00:25:12.577 --> 00:25:14.910 align:middle line:84%
when you create a program for
somebody who's really sick

00:25:14.910 --> 00:25:17.520 align:middle line:84%
and you want to intervene with
them in terms of detoxing them

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:19.645 align:middle line:84%
from the medications they've
taken, supporting them

00:25:19.645 --> 00:25:20.970 align:middle line:90%
with neurotransmitter remedies.

00:25:20.970 --> 00:25:24.630 align:middle line:84%
This is very much a field
that's developing at the moment.

00:25:24.630 --> 00:25:27.840 align:middle line:84%
So she's doing more
of that than I am.

00:25:27.840 --> 00:25:29.370 align:middle line:84%
I'm still the
classical practitioner

00:25:29.370 --> 00:25:31.410 align:middle line:84%
who prefers to work
with single remedies

00:25:31.410 --> 00:25:34.470 align:middle line:84%
and really delve the
psychological profile.

00:25:34.470 --> 00:25:37.140 align:middle line:84%
But this is an important--
this is an emerging

00:25:37.140 --> 00:25:39.117 align:middle line:84%
development in homeopathy,
very similar to what

00:25:39.117 --> 00:25:40.950 align:middle line:84%
I would say is what
happened with functional

00:25:40.950 --> 00:25:43.050 align:middle line:84%
medicine in
conventional medicine.

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:46.530 align:middle line:84%
Functional medicine developed
outside the medical schools,

00:25:46.530 --> 00:25:48.450 align:middle line:84%
outside the internal
medicine program,

00:25:48.450 --> 00:25:51.720 align:middle line:84%
but based on the work
of Geoffrey Bland.

00:25:51.720 --> 00:25:54.180 align:middle line:90%
And it's really taken off.

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:55.550 align:middle line:90%
So this is sort of a parallel.

00:25:55.550 --> 00:25:57.675 align:middle line:84%
This is like functional
medicine within homeopathy.

00:25:57.675 --> 00:25:59.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Does
functional medicine

00:25:59.460 --> 00:26:01.170 align:middle line:90%
employ the use of homeopathics?

00:26:01.170 --> 00:26:02.760 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: No.

00:26:02.760 --> 00:26:03.630 align:middle line:90%
Not conventionally.

00:26:03.630 --> 00:26:03.810 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:26:03.810 --> 00:26:04.170 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:26:04.170 --> 00:26:06.510 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: But it's a functional
way, a systems-wide way

00:26:06.510 --> 00:26:09.030 align:middle line:84%
of looking at a client as
opposed to breaking you down

00:26:09.030 --> 00:26:11.730 align:middle line:84%
like in a gastroenterologist
for your gastric system,

00:26:11.730 --> 00:26:15.030 align:middle line:84%
a psychiatrist for your
mind, and a neurologist

00:26:15.030 --> 00:26:15.990 align:middle line:90%
for your nerves.

00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:17.820 align:middle line:84%
At least within
conventional medicine

00:26:17.820 --> 00:26:19.853 align:middle line:84%
there was this attempt
to look at someone

00:26:19.853 --> 00:26:20.770 align:middle line:90%
at a functional level.

00:26:20.770 --> 00:26:23.170 align:middle line:84%
But the problem there
still is the consciousness,

00:26:23.170 --> 00:26:26.568 align:middle line:84%
which is so central to how
homeopathy works, who you are,

00:26:26.568 --> 00:26:28.860 align:middle line:84%
what has happened to you at
the level of consciousness,

00:26:28.860 --> 00:26:31.630 align:middle line:84%
that is not part of functional
medicine as I know it.

00:26:31.630 --> 00:26:34.635 align:middle line:84%
You're still sort of treated
like a mechanical object.

00:26:34.635 --> 00:26:35.680 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: It's anecdotal.

00:26:35.680 --> 00:26:36.480 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:26:36.480 --> 00:26:40.020 align:middle line:84%
In homeopathy, who
you are consciously,

00:26:40.020 --> 00:26:42.540 align:middle line:84%
experiences that you've
had, what has traumatized,

00:26:42.540 --> 00:26:43.710 align:middle line:90%
what your hot button is--

00:26:43.710 --> 00:26:44.010 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:26:44.010 --> 00:26:45.210 align:middle line:84%
I was just going
to ask you, that's

00:26:45.210 --> 00:26:46.610 align:middle line:84%
the first question
you ask people.

00:26:46.610 --> 00:26:47.790 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: Well,
it's not the first,

00:26:47.790 --> 00:26:48.940 align:middle line:90%
but it's an important one.

00:26:48.940 --> 00:26:51.600 align:middle line:84%
I let them talk and let my
clients talk for quite a while

00:26:51.600 --> 00:26:55.170 align:middle line:84%
before I ask that because I want
to get at my own sense of what

00:26:55.170 --> 00:26:56.230 align:middle line:90%
it might be.

00:26:56.230 --> 00:26:58.230 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, it's a very
important question to ask.

00:26:58.230 --> 00:26:59.605 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: What's
your hot button?

00:26:59.605 --> 00:27:01.740 align:middle line:90%
What's really sets you off?

00:27:01.740 --> 00:27:05.110 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: There's two ways
of asking that question.

00:27:05.110 --> 00:27:05.910 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:27:05.910 --> 00:27:08.443 align:middle line:84%
What's your least favorite
situation to be in?

00:27:08.443 --> 00:27:09.860 align:middle line:84%
Let's say you're
in that situation

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:12.800 align:middle line:84%
that I had a video camera on
you, what would I see in here?

00:27:12.800 --> 00:27:15.120 align:middle line:84%
What would you do after
your button is pushed?

00:27:15.120 --> 00:27:15.920 align:middle line:90%
Do you get drunk?

00:27:15.920 --> 00:27:17.337 align:middle line:84%
Do you punch
somebody in the nose?

00:27:17.337 --> 00:27:18.480 align:middle line:90%
Do you write a poem?

00:27:18.480 --> 00:27:19.318 align:middle line:90%
Do you overeat?

00:27:19.318 --> 00:27:20.610 align:middle line:90%
Do you withdraw into your room?

00:27:20.610 --> 00:27:21.485 align:middle line:90%
Do you get irritable?

00:27:21.485 --> 00:27:22.310 align:middle line:90%
What do you do?

00:27:22.310 --> 00:27:25.325 align:middle line:84%
That question has-- it's a
very, very powerful question.

00:27:25.325 --> 00:27:27.560 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Because this
is also associated

00:27:27.560 --> 00:27:30.560 align:middle line:84%
with what might show
up as illness in them?

00:27:30.560 --> 00:27:31.820 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Absolutely.

00:27:31.820 --> 00:27:33.050 align:middle line:90%
Absolutely.

00:27:33.050 --> 00:27:35.210 align:middle line:90%
Homeopathy is one-stop shopping.

00:27:35.210 --> 00:27:38.720 align:middle line:84%
That is my entryway
into somebody.

00:27:38.720 --> 00:27:41.870 align:middle line:84%
It's funny how hard it
is to get this clear.

00:27:41.870 --> 00:27:44.330 align:middle line:84%
The mind and the body are
absolutely inseparable as far

00:27:44.330 --> 00:27:45.440 align:middle line:90%
as this kind of work goes.

00:27:45.440 --> 00:27:45.710 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:27:45.710 --> 00:27:47.570 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about one
of the most common

00:27:47.570 --> 00:27:49.850 align:middle line:84%
and ubiquitous
conditions to humanity,

00:27:49.850 --> 00:27:53.270 align:middle line:84%
and it's psychospiritual, and
it goes deep, back, back, back.

00:27:53.270 --> 00:27:56.386 align:middle line:84%
And that is the
fear of abandonment.

00:27:56.386 --> 00:27:57.450 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:27:57.450 --> 00:27:57.705 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:27:57.705 --> 00:27:59.640 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Talking about
that, how would you

00:27:59.640 --> 00:28:01.740 align:middle line:84%
approach that with a
person, the fear of abandon?

00:28:01.740 --> 00:28:03.480 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: I wish you had given
me another hour and a half.

00:28:03.480 --> 00:28:04.230 align:middle line:90%
It takes the case of--

00:28:04.230 --> 00:28:05.610 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, take
5 or 10 minutes.

00:28:05.610 --> 00:28:06.410 align:middle line:90%
You've got time.

00:28:06.410 --> 00:28:07.215 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: OK.

00:28:07.215 --> 00:28:09.090 align:middle line:84%
You know I've got a book
coming out next year

00:28:09.090 --> 00:28:13.470 align:middle line:84%
called the "Emotional Causes
of Chronic Illness Homeopathy

00:28:13.470 --> 00:28:14.790 align:middle line:90%
for Existential Stress."

00:28:14.790 --> 00:28:17.860 align:middle line:84%
So abandonment would be one
of those existential issues.

00:28:17.860 --> 00:28:19.980 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't just mean--
we're using that word a lot

00:28:19.980 --> 00:28:21.260 align:middle line:84%
these days because
of climate change

00:28:21.260 --> 00:28:23.218 align:middle line:84%
and we say, oh, my God,
we're all going to die.

00:28:23.218 --> 00:28:26.220 align:middle line:84%
But existential actually
means many, many more things

00:28:26.220 --> 00:28:28.500 align:middle line:90%
psychologically.

00:28:28.500 --> 00:28:30.720 align:middle line:84%
So abandoned, if I was
taking someone's case

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:34.000 align:middle line:84%
and this was coming up,
that one word would not

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:34.800 align:middle line:90%
give me the remedy.

00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:36.592 align:middle line:84%
I would actually want
the person to tell me

00:28:36.592 --> 00:28:38.250 align:middle line:90%
the story of their abandonment.

00:28:38.250 --> 00:28:41.250 align:middle line:84%
And I'd find out whether
they were actually orphaned

00:28:41.250 --> 00:28:44.250 align:middle line:84%
or if someone was just a
completely unavailable parent.

00:28:44.250 --> 00:28:47.610 align:middle line:84%
Or was there a sibling who
was responsible for them

00:28:47.610 --> 00:28:48.410 align:middle line:90%
who betrayed them.

00:28:48.410 --> 00:28:49.993 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's so
many parts of that.

00:28:49.993 --> 00:28:52.770 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Each one that creates
a different kind of feeling

00:28:52.770 --> 00:28:54.550 align:middle line:90%
or experience, those nuances.

00:28:54.550 --> 00:28:55.350 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:28:55.350 --> 00:28:57.433 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I'd have to teach
you homeopathy about it,

00:28:57.433 --> 00:28:59.700 align:middle line:84%
but I'll give you some
examples, remedies

00:28:59.700 --> 00:29:01.500 align:middle line:90%
that talk about abandonment.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:04.020 align:middle line:84%
If you needed a remedy
like magnesium carbonicum

00:29:04.020 --> 00:29:07.470 align:middle line:90%
or magnesium moriadicum.

00:29:07.470 --> 00:29:10.710 align:middle line:84%
One flavor of abandonment
there would be your parents

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:12.720 align:middle line:84%
would have been fighting
all the time, fighting

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:14.070 align:middle line:90%
and at each other's throats.

00:29:14.070 --> 00:29:16.470 align:middle line:84%
And that would have created
a great sense of insecurity

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:16.950 align:middle line:90%
for you.

00:29:16.950 --> 00:29:19.260 align:middle line:84%
And you would have become
a peacemaker, a terrible--

00:29:19.260 --> 00:29:21.900 align:middle line:84%
and you would have you'd be
prone to big ups and downs.

00:29:21.900 --> 00:29:24.090 align:middle line:84%
Part of that picture,
you might become

00:29:24.090 --> 00:29:27.090 align:middle line:84%
as a result of that or
a reflection of that

00:29:27.090 --> 00:29:29.940 align:middle line:84%
have a problem with
gluten and with dairy

00:29:29.940 --> 00:29:31.580 align:middle line:90%
and be very, very up and down.

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:33.330 align:middle line:84%
That's the piece that
would be someone who

00:29:33.330 --> 00:29:34.350 align:middle line:90%
feels like they are an orphan.

00:29:34.350 --> 00:29:36.365 align:middle line:84%
They might not have
actually been an orphan.

00:29:36.365 --> 00:29:40.020 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: So that's kind of
under that very big umbrella

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:41.500 align:middle line:90%
of various forms of abandonment.

00:29:41.500 --> 00:29:42.300 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: Yeah.

00:29:42.300 --> 00:29:44.490 align:middle line:84%
Now, the poster
child for abandonment

00:29:44.490 --> 00:29:45.945 align:middle line:90%
is a remedy called pulsatilla.

00:29:45.945 --> 00:29:46.790 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Oh, yeah.

00:29:46.790 --> 00:29:48.510 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: OK?

00:29:48.510 --> 00:29:51.480 align:middle line:84%
Pulsatilla, and it's mostly
for women or if men needed it,

00:29:51.480 --> 00:29:53.580 align:middle line:84%
it would be boys up
to the age of 12.

00:29:53.580 --> 00:29:56.580 align:middle line:84%
And that's a feeling
of really genuinely,

00:29:56.580 --> 00:29:57.570 align:middle line:90%
oh, you don't love me.

00:29:57.570 --> 00:29:59.520 align:middle line:84%
I mean, you don't
love me anymore.

00:29:59.520 --> 00:30:00.610 align:middle line:90%
You're not there.

00:30:00.610 --> 00:30:02.160 align:middle line:84%
And so people who
need that remedy,

00:30:02.160 --> 00:30:04.290 align:middle line:84%
they cry at the drop
of a hat and they're

00:30:04.290 --> 00:30:06.180 align:middle line:90%
also prone to sinus infection.

00:30:06.180 --> 00:30:08.790 align:middle line:84%
But there's also things
that are good about them

00:30:08.790 --> 00:30:10.680 align:middle line:84%
that we don't want
to change them,

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:11.970 align:middle line:90%
but they actually are clues.

00:30:11.970 --> 00:30:14.880 align:middle line:84%
Someone who needs pulsatilla
will love to be outdoors,

00:30:14.880 --> 00:30:16.230 align:middle line:90%
they will love fresh air.

00:30:16.230 --> 00:30:17.970 align:middle line:84%
They'll have a very
sympathetic quality.

00:30:17.970 --> 00:30:20.220 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to change
that, but you relate to that.

00:30:20.220 --> 00:30:22.350 align:middle line:84%
You feel that as a
homeopath with someone.

00:30:22.350 --> 00:30:23.760 align:middle line:90%
Use your own feelings.

00:30:23.760 --> 00:30:25.125 align:middle line:90%
This person is very sympathetic.

00:30:25.125 --> 00:30:27.900 align:middle line:84%
I mean, their whole
being cries out to me.

00:30:27.900 --> 00:30:30.312 align:middle line:84%
If someone has an
annoying personality,

00:30:30.312 --> 00:30:32.520 align:middle line:84%
we don't dismiss them say,
I don't want to treat you.

00:30:32.520 --> 00:30:34.180 align:middle line:84%
We say, oh, that's
my feeling you.

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:35.485 align:middle line:90%
I have to use that here.

00:30:35.485 --> 00:30:37.110 align:middle line:84%
Why am I feeling that
from this person?

00:30:37.110 --> 00:30:38.430 align:middle line:90%
What are they projecting?

00:30:38.430 --> 00:30:40.230 align:middle line:84%
Well, is the
pulsatilla the person

00:30:40.230 --> 00:30:42.000 align:middle line:84%
is very sympathetic
and very lovable

00:30:42.000 --> 00:30:44.670 align:middle line:84%
and you just want to
go give them a hug.

00:30:44.670 --> 00:30:48.420 align:middle line:84%
But this is a very
stereotypical kind of a picture.

00:30:48.420 --> 00:30:49.395 align:middle line:90%
Homeopathy has many--

00:30:49.395 --> 00:30:51.055 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: We're all
cracks, as you say.

00:30:51.055 --> 00:30:51.930 align:middle line:90%
>>KANTOR: All cracks.

00:30:51.930 --> 00:30:53.940 align:middle line:84%
But it's also what
we now might call

00:30:53.940 --> 00:30:56.430 align:middle line:84%
political incorrectness
is that much of the time,

00:30:56.430 --> 00:30:57.990 align:middle line:90%
it comes up for blondes.

00:30:57.990 --> 00:30:59.560 align:middle line:90%
It's not my choice.

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:01.710 align:middle line:84%
It's just it's a certain
kind of a picture.

00:31:01.710 --> 00:31:03.210 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Kind of
overly empathetic,

00:31:03.210 --> 00:31:05.010 align:middle line:84%
fear of abandonment,
and all of this.

00:31:05.010 --> 00:31:07.050 align:middle line:84%
>>KANTOR: Other kinds
of abandonment remedies.

00:31:07.050 --> 00:31:08.340 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:31:08.340 --> 00:31:10.830 align:middle line:84%
I'll tell you this, this is
really interesting in terms

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:14.220 align:middle line:84%
of, to me, existential
issues even for children,

00:31:14.220 --> 00:31:17.420 align:middle line:84%
OK, because I just came
upon this the other day.

00:31:17.420 --> 00:31:19.730 align:middle line:84%
There's a remedy
whose keynote is

00:31:19.730 --> 00:31:22.310 align:middle line:84%
fear of falling
forward, falling down.

00:31:22.310 --> 00:31:25.320 align:middle line:84%
And it's a major
remedy for children.

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:26.870 align:middle line:90%
It's called borax.

00:31:26.870 --> 00:31:30.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, for a child the
feeling of being put down

00:31:30.320 --> 00:31:33.500 align:middle line:84%
is an existential problem
because it means separation

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:34.940 align:middle line:90%
from the mother.

00:31:34.940 --> 00:31:38.390 align:middle line:84%
So I have this one
child who I tried

00:31:38.390 --> 00:31:40.280 align:middle line:90%
to give borax to the other day.

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:43.350 align:middle line:84%
She's actually I think
12 years old now.

00:31:43.350 --> 00:31:45.440 align:middle line:84%
But this remedy, this
state has come up.

00:31:45.440 --> 00:31:47.480 align:middle line:84%
And when I discussed
it with her mother,

00:31:47.480 --> 00:31:50.570 align:middle line:84%
we talked about how at
birth this particular child

00:31:50.570 --> 00:31:52.460 align:middle line:84%
right after birth she
had had a heart defect.

00:31:52.460 --> 00:31:54.140 align:middle line:84%
And she had to
have surgery, and.

00:31:54.140 --> 00:31:57.590 align:middle line:84%
She was tremendously congested
and whenever she was put down,

00:31:57.590 --> 00:32:00.410 align:middle line:84%
she wailed and
